    "Unknown": "Verse 4 Was arrayed ( \u00ean peribebl\u00eamen\u00ea ). Periphrastic past perfect indicative of periball\u00f4 , to fling round one. In purple and scarlet ( porphuroun kai kokkinon ). Accusative retained after this passive verb of clothing, as so often. Porphurous is old adjective for purple (from porphura ), in N.T. only here and John `[char_John_Ref]` 19:2,\n4. This is a picture of the beast of Rev 13:1 which the woman is riding, but no longer just the empire, but one of the emperors who died ( ouk estin , is not). And is about to come up out of the abyss ( kai mellei anabainein ek t\u00eas abussou ). That is, he is going to come to life again. And to go into perdition ( kai eis ap\u00f4leian hupagei ). So (and he goes into perdition) the best MSS. read rather than the infinitive hupagein . Most interpreters see here an allusion to the &quot;Nero redivivus &quot; expectancy realized in Domitian, who was ruling when John `[char_John_Ref]` wrote and who was called Nero redivivus . Shall wonder ( thaumasth\u00easontai ). First future passive (deponent) of thaumaz\u00f4 , with which compare ethaumasth\u00ea in Rev 13:\nVerse 4\n4. Verse 4 Was arrayed (\u00ean peribebl\u00eamen\u00ea). Periphrastic past perfect indicative of periball\u00f4, to fling round one. In purple and scarlet (porphuroun kai kokkinon). Accusative retained after this passive verb of clothing, as so often. Porphurous is old adjective for purple [v_Jhn_19_2] (from porphura), in N.T. only here and John `[char_John_Ref]` 19:2,\n4. This is a picture of [v_Rev_13_1] the beast of Rev 13:1 which the woman is riding, but no longer just the empire, but one of the emperors who died (ouk estin, is not). And is about to come up out of the abyss (kai mellei anabainein ek t\u00eas abussou). That is, he is going to come to life again. And to go into perdition (kai eis ap\u00f4leian hupagei). So (and he goes into perdition) the best MSS. read rather than the infinitive hupagein. Most interpreters see here an allusion to the \"Nero redivivus\" expectancy realized in Domitian, who was ruling when John `[char_John_Ref]` wrote and who was called Nero redivivus. Shall wonder (thaumasth\u00easontai). First future passive (deponent) of thaumaz\u00f4, [v_Rev_13_3] with which compare ethaumasth\u00ea in Rev 13:\nVerse 4 And they sat upon them (kai ekathisan ep' autous). First aorist active indicative of kathiz\u00f4. Another period here apparently [v_Rev_20_7] synchronous (verse Rev 20:7) with the confinement of Satan in the abyss. No subject is given for this plural verb. Apparently Christ and [v_Mat_19_28] the Apostles (Mat 19:28; Luke 22:30) and some of the saints (1Co 6:3), martyrs some hold. Judgment was given unto them (krima edoth\u00ea autois). First aorist passive of did\u00f4mi. Picture of the heavenly court of assizes. The souls (tas psuchas). Accusative after eidon at the beginning of the verse. Of them that had been beheaded (t\u00f4n pepelekismen\u00f4n). Genitive of the articular perfect passive participle of pelekiz\u00f4, old word (from pelekus an axe, the traditional instrument for execution in republican Rome, but later supplanted [v_Rev_6_9] by the sword), to cut off with an axe, here only in N.T. See Rev 6:9; [v_Rev_18_24] Rev 18:24; Rev 19:2 for previous mention of these martyrs for the [v_Rev_1_9] witness of Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` (Rev 1:9; Rev 12:17; Rev 19:10). Others also besides martyrs shared in Christ's victory, those who refused to [v_Rev_13_15] worship the beast or wear his mark as in Rev 13:15; Rev 14:9; Rev [v_Rev_19_20] 16:2; Rev 19:\n4. The scene is prepared for the last judgment often mentioned in the N.T. (Mat [v_Rom_14_10] 25:31-46; Rom 14:10; 2Co 5:10). \"The absolute purity of this Supreme Court is symbolized by the colour of the Throne\" (Swete) [v_Dan_7_9] as in Dan 7:9; Ps 9:1; Ps 97:",
